WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:03.000
Sorry about that.

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:06.000
My name is Melissa, and this is Sharon.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.000
We are two of the developers working on Positron.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Through developing Positron, connecting with users in the GitHub repository,

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:19.000
and our own experiences using code editors,

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.000
we've gathered some tips and tricks to share with you today.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Our hope is that there's something in here for everyone,

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:27.000
whether you've yet to download Positron,

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:33.000
or you've been following along from the dailies from the beginning.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.000
So we've broken the tips and tricks into three sections.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:39.000
First, we'll cover navigating Positron

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:44.000
and a few ways you may want to personalize your coding space.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Then, we'll dive into how you can set yourself up

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.000
for a more pleasant data exploration experience

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.000
with a closer look at our editing and plotting tools.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:55.000
And finally, we'll cover some tricks

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:59.000
on how to effectively pair with Positron's AI assistant,

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:04.000
currently available as a preview feature, Positron Assistant.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.000
So let's start with personalizing your coding space.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.000
We're going to cover how to effectively navigate through Positron

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.000
and configure your layout and settings.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:17.000
We'll start out by familiarizing ourselves with the command palette.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
The command palette is a text-driven interface

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
that allows you to access almost any action that's possible in Positron.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:27.000
It's your gateway to finding and running any command

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:31.000
without clicking through menus or memorizing keyboard shortcuts.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:33.000
It's fuzzy searchable,

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
so even if you don't remember the name of a command

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
or you aren't sure what commands are available,

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
you can type a few letters or words and see what your options are.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.000
This feature will allow you to quickly access

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.000
many of the other commands that we have to share with you today.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.000
So if you're not already using the command palette

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
as part of your daily workflow, this is a really great habit to build

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:59.000
to help familiarize yourself with Positron.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:03.000
All right, so let's start building that habit right away.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.000
Let's open up the command palette

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:13.000
and run the command, welcome open walkthrough.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:18.000
So we ran the command, welcome.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.000
We're running the command, welcome open walkthrough.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:27.000
And then we'll type migrating and select one of these walkthroughs.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
Positron will open up one of these walkthroughs,

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:33.000
and these will provide step-by-step guidance

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:38.000
on how to get situated in Positron.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.000
These are a great way to learn how to migrate

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:47.000
from VS Code or from RStudio.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.000
Now if you're looking for, for example,

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:51.000
the four-pane data science layout,

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:53.000
which you may be familiar with from RStudio,

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.000
you can run the command, view stacked layout.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
Once you do that, you'll be presented with your files,

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:04.000
your code editor, your variables, console,

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.000
and plots all in one view.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.000
If you want even more customization,

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.000
you can run the command, customize layout,

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.000
or here we've searched for view layout,

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.000
and we've got all these other options for you to try out.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
Next up, we'll jump over to the interpreter picker

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.000
in the top right of Positron.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
The picker shows the interpreter for the active console session.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:37.000
The active session provides the data you see in the variables pane.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:39.000
The picker is especially helpful

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.000
when you have multiple console sessions going,

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:47.000
so you can tell which session is currently active.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:49.000
Speaking of multiple sessions,

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:52.000
you can create them for various R and Python runtimes

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
by clicking on the plus button in the console.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
If you click into the dropdown by the plus button,

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:01.000
you can select a different interpreter

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:05.000
if you don't want to use the active interpreter.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Now if you've got a few consoles going,

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
it can start to get confusing which console is for what.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:14.000
So one of Isabelle's favorite features to renaming your console,

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:18.000
you can right-click on a console session to rename it,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:23.000
and you can even include emojis if you want.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.000
One more console tip.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.000
There's this little info icon in the console,

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:28.000
and if you click on that,

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.000
you will get some metadata about the console,

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
like the interpreter path

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:37.000
or some quick links to relevant output channel logs.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:38.000
And as Isabelle mentioned,

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
Ruby is going to be doing a lightning talk later today on multi-console,

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.000
so stay tuned for that if you want to learn more.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:48.000
All right.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.000
Up next we have key bindings.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:53.000
You're likely already familiar with what a key binding is,

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:55.000
but just to review,

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:57.000
it's the association of a specific key

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:00.000
or a combination of keys with a command.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:02.000
So to get to the key bindings UI,

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:06.000
you can run the command preferences open keyboard shortcuts,

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.000
and you can bind any command

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
that you can run through the command palette.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.000
When you find yourself using the same command frequently,

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:17.000
you can check if a key binding exists

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.000
and add your own if it doesn't.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:20.000
The simplest way to do this

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.000
is to use the keyboard shortcuts editor.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.000
But for more granularity,

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.000
you may want to edit key bindings.json directly.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
So you can do this by running the command

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:35.000
open keyboard shortcuts json.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:37.000
In this example,

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
I'm taking advantage of a built-in command, run commands,

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
that allows you to chain together multiple commands

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:45.000
into a single key bindings.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:49.000
Here I'm using the kill terminal and new terminal commands

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.000
to create a quick way to restart my terminal.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:54.000
I'm using the when clause

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:59.000
so that the binding is only active when my focus is in the terminal,

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:05.000
leaving the key binding available for other scenarios as well.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:11.000
So now we're going to move on to tips for exploring your data.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:14.000
We'll start off by introducing the Data Explorer.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.000
The interface is divided into a filter bar,

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
data grid, and summary panel.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
The summary panel shows each column's name,

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.000
its data type, and the percentage of missing values,

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:28.000
and it even includes a small histogram.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.000
And you can view data frames you've loaded

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.000
into your session variables,

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
but you can also click on your data file in the File Explorer,

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
and it will automatically open in the Data Explorer.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:43.000
You can do this with compressed files as well,

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:46.000
no manual unzipping required.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:51.000
What if I just want to see the raw CSV file?

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:52.000
Well, you're in luck,

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:56.000
because that is also as simple as the click of a button.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.000
As we can see here, viewing your plain text file

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
just requires clicking here,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
and you can easily open two tabs

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:07.000
and switch between the Data Explorer and raw text file.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:10.000
The Data Explorer watches your source,

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:16.000
so any changes made to your CSV file will be reflected instantly.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:19.000
So if you're interested in learning more about the Data Explorer,

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.000
stick around in this room.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:27.000
Wes McKinney has a talk for exploring datasets in Positron.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:28.000
All right.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:33.000
Have you ever found yourself lost in a sea of editor tabs,

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.000
trying to find that one file?

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:38.000
You're scrolling back and forth through all the file tabs.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:42.000
You're starting to forget which file you're even looking for.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:45.000
Wouldn't it be nice if you could just pin the tabs

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:49.000
that you care about so much so you don't have to lose them?

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:53.000
Well, we've got some good news.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
You can pin editor tabs.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:56.000
They can be code files.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:58.000
They can be the Settings tab.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:02.000
They can be a Data Explorer that you want easy access to.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:05.000
All you have to do is right-click on the Editor tab

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:07.000
and click Pin,

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:09.000
and those tabs will be pinned

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:13.000
to the beginning of your open editors.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:14.000
So I really love this feature,

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
but sometimes I still feel like

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:19.000
I'm getting lost in a sea of editor tabs.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:20.000
Well, okay.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:24.000
Well, you may want to reevaluate the ones you really need

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:25.000
if you're pinning them,

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
but in the meantime, you can use this setting,

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:31.000
Pin Tabs on Separate Row.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.000
So if you enable this,

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:34.000
you get a little bit more real estate,

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:38.000
and you get your pinned tabs above your other tabs.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.000
Very nice.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
Now on to plots.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:47.000
Do you ever wish you could open up your plot in a larger space?

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:52.000
Maybe you want to see the Iris dataset in full screen.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.000
You can do this by clicking on this little button here

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
in the Plots pane to open the plot in a new window

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.000
or an editor tab.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:04.000
Now we're just going to do a spontaneous theme change,

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:09.000
so let's switch over to Positron Dark here.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.000
Ooh, sharing.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:12.000
My eyes.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.000
What happened to the dark mode?

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
Oh, yeah.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.000
Well, this is what you will get if you export this plot as an image,

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:24.000
but during your authoring and editing process,

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:27.000
we can de-ruin your dark mode

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:30.000
by clicking on this circle button in the Plots pane.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
This allows you to configure

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:35.000
whether plots should have a filter applied to them.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:38.000
By default, no filter is applied,

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
but you can configure this to follow your theme

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.000
or you can select a dark filter

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:46.000
if you are just super into dark plots all the time.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:50.000
So let's go ahead and choose Follow Theme.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
And all is well now.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:55.000
Agreed. Much better.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
With that, let's move on to talking about

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
effectively pairing with Positron Assistant.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:04.000
Positron Assistant is an AI client

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:07.000
that provides LLM integration with Positron

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.000
through chat and inline completions.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.000
It's great for helping with debugging, refactoring,

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.000
or getting suggestions for the next steps

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.000
that you should take in your project.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
Two concepts that you should really understand

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
to make the best use of Assistant are context and tools.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:27.000
Context refers to the information

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:31.000
that Positron Assistant provides to the LLM alongside your prompt.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.000
Positron Assistant provides context about files and folders,

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:40.000
and it also provides your in-memory data from your session.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
So this includes your loaded variables, plots pane,

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:47.000
active console sessions, and session state.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
With your permission, Assistant can even run code

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:53.000
directly in your active session.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
You can take advantage of this context

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:58.000
by asking Assistant to plot data frames for you

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:03.000
or tweak things like the title or access labels on your plots.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:07.000
You can view what context Assistant is passing to the LLM

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
in your chat context.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:12.000
So here we ask Assistant about the current plot

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.000
with the console session enabled as context.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
Assistant has access to review the plot

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
as well as the code that generated the plot.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:26.000
And you can see this because the open eye icon

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:30.000
is open next to the context.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:34.000
What about closing the eye? What if we want it closed?

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:35.000
You can close the eye.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:39.000
You can control exactly what context Assistant sends to the LLM.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
So whether you have security concerns

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
or the context is just irrelevant to your prompt,

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:50.000
you can close your eye by clicking the eye icon.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
So in this example, we've removed access

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
to the console session context.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:58.000
Assistant is aware that you have a plot,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:11:59.000
but it cannot see the plot

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:04.000
nor the code that generated the plot.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
Providing relevant contextual information

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
can yield better results from AI models,

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
so there may be even more context

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
that you want to provide to Assistant.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.000
You can do this by clicking add context

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:20.000
to attach additional context such as files and folders,

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:26.000
and you can even add additional interpreter sessions as well.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
Much of this context is provided to the LLM

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
through tool calling.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
So for example, if you ask a question

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
about the current plot,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
Positron Assistant will call the get plot tool,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
and that will allow the active plot image

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
to be included with your question.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:43.000
Without the get plot tool,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:49.000
the AI model isn't actually able to see your image.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:52.000
If you want to check if Positron Assistant has called a tool,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:55.000
you can keep an eye out for this green check mark

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:58.000
followed by some text describing an action.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:03.000
So in this case, we have viewed the active plot.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
By default, Positron will call tools

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
that seem relevant to your prompt,

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
but it can be helpful to attach tools as context.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:15.000
So if you want Assistant to utilize specific tools

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:16.000
with your prompt,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
you can click on add context in the chat,

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:20.000
and then tools,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:26.000
and you'll be able to pick a tool to include as your context.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
Let's now take a look at a couple other tools

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.000
available with Positron Assistant.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
The get an R help page tool

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:36.000
looks at your current R session and loaded packages

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:41.000
and retrieves help and vignettes content for that package.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:44.000
The AI model is then provided with this content

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
so that you can get guidance

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:51.000
directly based on the package's documentation.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.000
Another tool Positron Assistant provides

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
is the get changed files tool,

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.000
which retrieves your file modifications from Git.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:00.000
If you want to use this tool,

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:05.000
include hashtag changes in your message to Assistant.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:08.000
So for example, here we've asked Assistant,

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.000
tell me about the hashtag changes I've made.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:14.000
So if Assistant can understand my changes,

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.000
does that mean it can just write the commit message for me?

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
Yeah, you could ask Assistant,

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.000
generate a commit message for my hashtag changes in the chat,

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:29.000
or here we've added axolotl and kangaroo to our code,

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
and from the source control panel,

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:35.000
we've clicked the sparkles button in the commit message box,

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
and Positron Assistant has generated

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:41.000
the commit message for us.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:43.000
Calling back to attach in context,

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.000
you can also select source control,

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.000
and this allows you to choose a specific commit

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.000
to include as context.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
Sometimes, like, a lot of code can change in a commit

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:57.000
if you're, like, changing a bunch of files,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:58.000
10,000 lines have changed,

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.000
or maybe it's just code that you're unfamiliar with,

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
so you can attach that commit as context

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.000
and then ask Assistant to help you understand

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.000
or summarize those changes.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:11.000
With these tips in mind,

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
we welcome you to try out Positron Assistant,

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:17.000
which is currently in preview in Positron.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.000
You'll need to enable the Positron Assistant enable setting,

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.000
so search for that in the settings UI

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
and check the checkbox,

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:27.000
and for more on Positron Assistant,

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:33.000
check out our docs at positron.posit.co.assistant.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.000
All right, we went over a lot of tips and tricks today,

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
so if you did miss anything,

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
the slides will be uploaded post-conf,

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
so keep an eye out for that,

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.000
and to learn more about Positron at conf,

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:48.000
Austin's up next to talk about remote SSH in Positron

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.000
and Wes shortly after with a talk on the Data Explorer,

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:55.000
and here are a few other sessions and demos

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
you might be interested in for more Positron content,

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
so keep an eye out for that in the conf schedule,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.000
and if you haven't seen it already,

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:05.000
there's a Positron lounge just outside this room

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:06.000
where the couches are

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:10.000
if you want a hands-on demo of Positron Assistant

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
or to chat with Positron devs,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
and we'll be there as well.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:18.000
All right, thank you, everyone, and open up for questions.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
applause

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
Thank you so much.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
I have a couple of questions here.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
So when defining new key bindings,

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
the autocomplete helps find commands.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:33.000
Where can I find the help slash description for that command,

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.000
including its arguments?

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:39.000
So just, I guess, general documentation

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:41.000
for the commands that are available,

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
if I'm interpreting that properly.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:50.000
Oh, it's not on.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.000
You know what, I'm going to join you on stage.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
We can pass around the mic.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.000
That should be on now.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:58.000
Hello.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:16:59.000
There we go.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.000
Okay.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
So if you're in Positron,

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
a good way to look for key bindings

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:10.000
is if you run the open up key bindings command.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:13.000
There is a UI that Melissa showed earlier

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
where you can search for key bindings.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:19.000
There's even a button that you can toggle,

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:22.000
and if you do a key binding like Command-C,

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
it will pull up all the commands that that corresponds to.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:28.000
A lot of the commands that you can use

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
are ones that we've inherited from VS Code as well,

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.000
so VS Code documentation would be a great place

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
to look that up as well.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.000
Awesome. Thank you.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:43.000
So I have two related questions.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
Can Positron Assistant be turned off,

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:50.000
and are there data leakage risks with Positron Assistant?

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
Do the LLMs have access to the underlying data,

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.000
or is that a feature that needs to be selected?

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:00.000
Yeah, so as Positron Assistant is currently in preview,

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
it is currently opt-in,

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.000
so it is disabled by default in builds of Positron.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
So to enable it,

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:12.000
you'll have to enable the Positron Assistant enable setting,

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.000
and if you do have Positron Assistant enabled,

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:18.000
Melissa was talking about the open eye,

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:21.000
closed eye icon in the chat pane.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:24.000
That allows you to include or exclude

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:27.000
your session context from your prompt.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.000
Your session context will have things

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
like the code that you ran in your console,

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:34.000
the variables you have loaded in your environment,

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
so if that's not something you want to include,

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
you can disable your context,

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
and that won't be sent over to the LLM.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:43.000
Great. We have lots of good questions here.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.000
I'll try and get a couple more in.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:48.000
So can you make keyboard shortcuts available to colleagues,

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:50.000
kind of like sharing preferences,

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:55.000
sharing key bindings?

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:59.000
Is it possible to share a preferences file

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:01.000
or something like that, or a key bindings file?

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:02.000
Yeah.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:03.000
Yeah?

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:06.000
Yeah, so the key bindings JSON file?

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:09.000
Right, so you can add them to the key bindings.json file,

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:12.000
and I believe you can even include that in a project.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:13.000
Is that right?

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:14.000
Oh, amazing.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:17.000
Yeah, so there's a .vs code directory

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.000
that will get created if you create

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:22.000
the key bindings.json file in your project,

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:25.000
and if multiple people are checking out that same project

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.000
or you're sharing that project,

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:30.000
that will be available as part of that specific project.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:33.000
Otherwise, your key bindings are at the user level,

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:36.000
so they'll be local to your machine.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
Amazing. I think we can fit one more in.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:42.000
So does Positron only allow R and Python coding?

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
Can extensions be used to introduce more interpreters

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:47.000
for other languages in the IDE?

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:50.000
Yep, so Positron's completely language agnostic,

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:54.000
so any of the VS code extensions or language packs

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:56.000
will work in Positron,

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:59.000
and yeah, that's one of the great things about it

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:02.000
is that it's not restricted to R and Python.

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:03.000
Amazing.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:07.000
The only limitation is that the interpreter-specific UI components

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:10.000
like the interpreter picker or the console sessions,

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:14.000
those right now we only have support for R and Python.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:16.000
Great. Thank you so much.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:17.000
Thank you.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:20.000
applause

